Let $\gamma$ be the ratio of $\frac{C_{p}}{C_{v}}$

<br/><br/>Then for adiabatic process

<br/><br/>$$
\begin{aligned}
& P V^{\gamma}=\text { Constant } \\\\
& \Rightarrow \frac{P_{i}}{P_{f}}=\left(\frac{V_{f}}{V_{i}}\right)^{\gamma} \\\\
& \Rightarrow \frac{81}{16}=\left(\frac{27}{8}\right)^{\gamma} \\\\
& \Rightarrow \gamma=\frac{4}{3}
\end{aligned}
$$

For monoatomic gas $\gamma_1=\frac{5}{3}$<br/><br/>
For diatomic gas at low temperatures<br/><br/>
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \gamma_2=\frac{7}{5} \\\\
& \therefore \frac{\gamma_1}{\gamma_2}=\frac{\frac{5}{3}}{\frac{7}{5}}=\frac{25}{21}
\end{aligned}
$$

